definition.value: Any 2-oxo monocarboxylic acid in which one of the terminal methyl hydrogens has been replaced by a methylthio group.
A 2-hydroxydicarboxylic acid that is any 2-alkylmalic acid in which one of the terminal methyl hydrogens has been replaced by a methylthio group.
A dicarboxylic acid having 2 or more units of unsaturation.
A 2-hydroxydicarboxylic acid that is any 3-alkylmalic acid in which one of the terminal methyl hydrogens has been replaced by a methylthio group.
A 3-(omega-methylthio)alkylmalic acid in which the 3-alkyl group is specified as 2-methylthioethyl.
A 2-hydroxydicarboxylic acid that is any 2-alkylmaleic acid in which one of the terminal methyl hydrogens has been replaced by a methylthio group.
A 2-(omega-methylthio)alkylmaleic acid in which the 2-alkyl group is specified as 2-methylthioethyl.
A 2-(omega-methylthio)alkylmaleic acid in which the 2-alkyl group is specified as 3-(methylthio)propyl.
A 3-(omega-methylthio)alkylmalic acid in which the 3-alkyl group is specified as 3-(methylthio)propyl.
A lyxonic acid that has D-configuration.
An aldonolactone obtained by cyclocondensation of the carboxy group and the 4-hydroxy group of D-lyxonic acid.
A ceramide 1-phosphate in which the sphingoid component is specified as phytosphingosine.
A phosphatidylserine 34:1 in which the 1-acyl group contains 16 carbons and no double bonds while the 2-acyl group contains 18 carbons and one double bond.
An oxo fatty acid that consists of docosahexaenoic acid (DoHE) carrying one or more oxo substituents.
An L-proline derivative that is trans-4-hydroxy-L-proline in which the amino hydrogen has been replaced by a methyl group.
An EC 1.8.1.* (oxidoreductase acting on sulfur group of donors, NAD+ or NADP+ as acceptor) inhibitor that interferes with the action of dihydrolipoyl dehydrogenase (EC 1.8.1.4).
A polyunsaturated oxo fatty acid anion that is the conjugate base of 15-oxo-EDE.

A furonaphthodioxole that is 4'-demethyldeoxypodophyllotoxin which is substituted at position 4 of the C-ring by a 2-{[2-(dimethylamino)ethyl](methyl)amino}ethyl group. While structurally related to etoposide, TOP-53 is significantly more toxic to non-small cell lung cancer cells, more active at generating chromosomal breaks, and displays improved cellular uptake and pharmacokinetics in animal lung tissues.
A N-acylsphingosine in which the ceramide N-acyl group is specified as pentacosanoyl.
A ceramide obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of icosanoic acid with the amino group of (4E,14Z)-sphinga-4,14-dienine.
A ceramide obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of docosanoic acid with the amino group of (4E,14Z)-sphinga-4,14-dienine.
A ceramide obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of tricosanoic acid with the amino group of (4E,14Z)-sphinga-4,14-dienine.
A cardiolipin in which three of the acyl groups are octadecadienoyl while the remaining one is octadecatrienoyl
A cardiolipin composed from two octadecatrienyl groups, one octadecenyl group and one icosatrieoyl group.
A cardiolipin in which the four acyl groups are specified as icosadienoyl, hexadecenoyl, octadecenoyl and octadecatrienoyl.
